Goals

  • Reproducible
  • Easy, top-quality plotting (data vis)
  • Encourages organisation, versioning, backups
  • Transferable skill

Outline

  • Why R & RStudio
  • Basic data structures & wrangling
  • Basic figures with ggplot2
  • Less basic figures
  • Custom examples by request

Why R

  • Free: no cost, open source
  • Portable across OSes
  • Language so work is documented, reviewable, re-useable
  • Flexible
  • Stats
  • Graphics

Why RStudio

  • Free: no cost, open source
  • Common integrated development environment (IDE)
  • Organises work into projects
  • Flexible

Why this workshop

  • Benefits of good data management
  • Encourage publication-quality figures
  • Improve clarity in calculations
  • Reduce problems of x versions of data in y spreadsheets
  • Skill you can develop & take with you
  • We don't do a good job training grad students on data handling, management, etc.

Data Structure

  • one column per observation type
  • one row per observation
  • no junk
  • no poor quality metadata

Aside: Split -- Apply -- Combine

plyr is a set of tools for a common set of problems:

split up a big data structure into homogeneous pieces

apply a function to each piece and then

combine all the results back together

for all types of data: array, list, data frmae, multiple inputs, nothing

Aside: Split -- Apply -- Combine

ddply(data, .(column), helper, other functions)

split data by the column

apply helper with other functions

combine results

install.packages('plyr')

library(plyr)
ddply(iris, .(Species), summarise, 
      mean.Sepal.Length = mean(Sepal.Length),
      sd.Sepal.Length = sd(Sepal.Length))

     Species mean.Sepal.Length sd.Sepal.Length
1     setosa             5.006       0.3524897
2 versicolor             5.936       0.5161711
3  virginica             6.588       0.6358796

Aside: dplyr

dplyr: A Grammar of Data Manipulation

verbs to describe common data manipulation tasks of data frames

  • filter, arrange, select, summarise
install.packages('dplyr')
detach("package:plyr")

library(dplyr)
summarise(group_by(iris, Species), 
          mean.Sepal.Length = mean(Sepal.Length),
          sd.Sepal.Length = sd(Sepal.Length))

Aside: dplyr and magrittr

Chain or pipe data from one verb to another:

iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  summarise(
          mean.Sepal.Length = mean(Sepal.Length),
          sd.Sepal.Length = sd(Sepal.Length)
          )

Grammar of Graphics

First:

  • data frame (data)
  • aesthetics (aes)
  • geometric objects (geom)

Second:

  • scales (scale)
  • facets (facet)
  • stats (stat)
  • coordinate system (coord)

Basic plot

  • need data (as a data frame), aes, geom
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(iris)


ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) + geom_point()


ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, colour = Species)) + geom_point()


ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, colour = Species)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth()


ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, colour = Species, size = Petal.Length)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth()


ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, colour = Species)) + geom_point(aes(size = Petal.Length)) + geom_smooth()


ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, colour = Species)) + geom_point(aes(size = Petal.Length)) + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

Language + Grammar

At some point the grammar becomes readable like a language

Take these data, plot that, use this shape + colour, add something on top, change the labels, add a stylistic theme, etc.

All reproducible and re-useable

Tweaks

More descriptive axis labels: labs()

Better or custom colours: scale_colour_*

Back to Doubs

ggplot(doubs, aes(x = NO3, y = O2, colour = BOD, size = Altitude)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  theme_light() +
  scale_colour_continuous(low = "green", high = "red") +
   labs(x = "NO3- (mg/L)",
        y = "O2 (mg/L)",
        colour = "BOD (mg/L)",
        size = "Altitude (masl)")

Back to Doubs with plotmath for special characters

ggplot(doubs, aes(x = NO3, y = O2, colour = BOD, size = Altitude)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  theme_light() +
  scale_colour_continuous(low = "green", high = "red") +
   labs(x = expression(NO[3]^-{}*" (mg/L)"), 
        y = expression(O[2]*" (mg/L)"),
        colour = "BOD (mg/L)",
        size = "Altitude (masl)")

Errorbars

Should have a column in our data frame for the error. Otherwise … specify manually.

Errorbars

Should have a column in our data frame for the error. Otherwise … specify manually.

ggplot(doubs, aes(x = NO3, y = O2)) + geom_point() + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymax = doubs$O2*1.05, ymin = doubs$O2*0.95), colour = "red") +
  geom_errorbarh(aes(xmax = doubs$NO3*1.05, xmin = doubs$NO3*0.95), colour = "blue")

Try this by adding columns to your doubs data frame.

Errorbars

# Make columns for the errorbars for NO3 and O2
doubs$NO3.min <- doubs$NO3 * 0.95
doubs$NO3.max <- doubs$NO3 * 1.05
doubs$O2.min <- doubs$O2 * 0.95
doubs$O2.max <- doubs$O2 * 1.05

Errorbars

doubs$NO3.min <- doubs$NO3 * 0.95
doubs$NO3.max <- doubs$NO3 * 1.05
doubs$O2.min <- doubs$O2 * 0.95
doubs$O2.max <- doubs$O2 * 1.05

ggplot(doubs, aes(x = NO3, y = O2)) + geom_point() + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymax = doubs$O2.max, ymin = doubs$O2.min), colour = "red") +
  geom_errorbarh(aes(xmax = doubs$NO3.max, xmin = doubs$NO3.min), colour = "blue") +
  labs(x = expression(NO[3]^-{}*" (mg/L)"), 
       y = expression(O[2]*" (mg/L)"),
       title = "Ta-Da!") +
  theme_linedraw(base_size = 24, base_family = "Times")
